MissionCommands.Message: Joe, what are you showing for GET now?
I think you wanted the GET, Jack, and the present GET is 96 hours 21 minutes. Over.
Okay, thank you.
And Jack, Houston. For your information, FIDO tells me that we are in the Earth's sphere of influence and we're starting to accelerate.
I thought it was about time we crossed. Thank you.
Roger.
We're on our way back home.
Houston, Aquarius.
Aquarius, Houston. Go ahead.

Okay, Vance. I just heard a little thump, sounded like down in the descent stage, and I saw a new shower of snowflakes come up that looked like they were emitted from down that way. We've already decided though ... I wonder what the Supercrit pressure looked like now.
Okay. Understand you saw a thump in the descent stage and a few snowflakes. We'll take a look down here, see if we see anything.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead.

Fred, we don't see anything wrong. For example, your SHe appears to be okay as far as we can see. The thing we don't have data on, is the start tank down there. [SHe, supercritical Helium tank, burst estimated to 106-107 hours MET]
Okay. And I doubt if it would have been that anyway.
Houston, Aquarius.
Go ahead, Jim.
Okay. We just had a battery warning Master Alarm, and it looks like it's battery 2.
Roger, Houston ... This is Houston. Could you close the Power Amp circuit breaker, and we'll get some high bit rate?
It's closed. Are you picking it up, Houston?
Roger. And we want to open the Bal Load Cross Tie on panel 16. Over.
It's open.
Okay. Could you turn off battery 2, and leave it off and let us look at it?
Okay. Battery 2 coming off the line.
Okay, Aquarius. So you want to stay in this configuration for a while, and let's look at the battery.
Roger. We'll stay in this configuration.
Want to close the Bal Loads circuit breaker back now.
We have it closed; the closed ... Balance Loads circuit breaker is closed.
Rog.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead, Houston.
Jim, on the battery problem, we have determined that it is not overcurrent or reverse current. We suspect it's over-temp, but don't know for sure, so we're going to watch it for a while.
Okay.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead, Houston.

Jim, regarding your number 2 battery, we think that it's probably a sensor failure, a temperature sensor failure that's caused this alarm, rather than an actual overtemp of the battery; the reason being that we haven't seen any higher temperatures in the glycol loop. We expect to put the battery back on about 101 hours. That'll be about 10 minutes, and then we'll look at it some more there. Over
Okay. Concerning number 2 battery, you think it might be a sensor failure because you haven't seen any changes, and you're going to put the battery back on the line in about 10 minutes.
That's affirm.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead, Vance.
Jim, we're ready to put that battery back on the line. Request you open the Cross Tie Bal Load circuit breaker, panel 16, and then put back Bat 2 back on the line.
Bat 2 is on the line. We have a Master Alarm and a Battery light.
Copy. And ... and we think that's probably an indication of the sensor problem, but stand by.
Jim, it looks to us like your battery is good, that this is in fact a sensor problem; therefore, request you close the Cross Tie Bal Loads on ... circuit breaker on panel 16.
Okay. We'll close the Cross Tie Balance Load circuit breaker at this time.
That's closed.
[This completes this mission, the journey continues in the next]

Title: MISSION 17 - STRANGE BURST
Description: The crew hears a strange burst from the Lunar Module.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
• to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
• to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
• to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
• to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.
